        <h1>LeetCode 3227: Vowels Game in a String (C++)</h1>

        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                Alice and Bob are playing a turn-based game on a string s. Alice goes first and must remove any non-empty substring that contains an odd number of vowels. Bob must remove any non-empty substring that contains an even number of vowels. The first player who cannot make a valid move loses. Both players play optimally. Return true if Alice wins, false if Bob wins.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: s = "leetcode" → Output: true (Alice can remove "leetcod" leaving "e", Bob cannot move)
                Input: s = "bbcd" → Output: false (Alice cannot make first move, no vowels)
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    bool doesAliceWin(string s) {
        // The key insight: Alice wins if and only if the string contains at least one vowel
        // 
        // Game theory analysis:
        // - If no vowels exist: Alice cannot make a move (needs odd vowels), Bob wins
        // - If odd number of vowels: Alice removes entire string (odd vowels), Alice wins
        // - If even number of vowels: Alice removes (total-1) vowels, leaving 1 vowel
        //   Bob then cannot move (1 is odd, not even), Alice wins
        
        const string vowels = "aeiou";
        
        // Check if any character in the string is a vowel
        for (char c : s) {
            if (vowels.find(c) != string::npos) {
                return true;  // Alice wins if any vowel exists
            }
        }
        
        return false;  // No vowels found, Alice cannot make a move
    }
};</code></pre>
